---
description: Repair omitted test coverage and verify the current ITL change
agent: code
---

Use this recovery command only from an active `itldev/*` development branch worktree when the current change may have skipped relevant Vanessa coverage or a complete verification cycle.

Begin one helper-owned repair session and retain the printed session id. It permits at most three full verification runs:

```powershell
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\.agents\skills\1c-workflow\scripts\agent-1c.ps1 -Action begin-verification-repair
```

1. Identify the current agent-made configuration/extension change from the user request, Git status/diff, and configured `exportPath`/`extensionsPath`. A Git-only refresh or merge from `master` is not an agent-made behavior change by itself.
2. Search configured `testsPath` for scenarios that exercise the changed observable behavior. Name the matching scenarios. If coverage is relevant and sufficient, reuse it unchanged: do not add or edit a test merely because this command was invoked.
3. Only when relevant coverage is missing, read `.agents/skills/1c-workflow/references/vanessa-tests.md` and add the smallest reliable scenario. A quick-fix normally needs one focused scenario; add another only for a separate meaningful boundary. If any `.feature` changes, run `/itl-vanessa-author` before the full repair check.
4. Run the existing helper directly from the current project directory with `timeout_ms >= 3900000` by default when supported; if the configured Designer timeout is higher than 3600 seconds, raise the outer timeout too. Do not use `120000 ms` or another short default because the helper may launch 1C Designer/Enterprise operations:

```powershell
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\.agents\skills\1c-workflow\scripts\agent-1c.ps1 -Action check-dev-branch -VerificationTrigger repair -RepairSessionId <session-id>
```

The helper owns the branch infobase update, Vanessa Automation `TESTMANAGER -> TESTCLIENT` run, JUnit/status/log evidence, and event-log baseline check. Do not run a separate base update first.

If verification fails, inspect the Vanessa report/status/log, the 1C log, event-log evidence, and the current change. Fix a defective scenario when the test is wrong; fix the implementation when the product change is wrong. After every edit rerun the full helper with the same repair session because previous evidence is stale. After three failed runs the helper refuses a fourth full run; then return blocker diagnostics and do not claim completion.

On fresh pass, report the reused or added scenario names, whether tests changed, the branch infobase update result, Vanessa report path, and event-log result.
